stylometry: Standard deviation is important because it tells us how closely the data are clustered around the mean of the distribution.  A large standard deviation tells us that the data are more widely scattered, while a small standard deviation indicates that the data are more closely clustered around the mean.  For example, a distribution with a mean of 50 and a standard deviation of 5 would tell us that 95% of the values in the distribution would fall between 40 and 60.  A distribution with a mean of 50 and a standard deviation of 20 would tell us that 95% of the values would fall between 10 and 90.  This indicates a widely scattered distribution which may not provide us with information that is very useful.
